<h2>Implementing JavaScript</h2>
In HTML, JavaScript code is embedded within <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;/script&gt;</code> tags.

<b>Example:</b>
<pre>
&lt;script&gt;
    document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "First JavaScript Example";
&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>

<b>Note:</b> The type attribute on script tag (type="text/javascript") is not necessary as JavaScript is the default scripting language in HTML.

<h3>JavaScript Functions and Events</h3>
A JavaScript function is a block of code that executes on invocation. For instance, a function can be invoked when an event like a button click occurs.

<h3>Position of JavaScript Code</h3>
Scripts can be positioned anywhere within an HTML document, either in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> or the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> section.

In the following examples, a JavaScript function is defined in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> and the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> sections respectively. It gets invoked on a button click.

<b>Example in &lt;head&gt; tag:</b>
<pre>
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
        &lt;script&gt;
            function myFunction() {
                document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Text has been changed.";
            }
        &lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;h2&gt;Example of JavaScript in &lt;head&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;

        &lt;p id="demo"&gt;A simple paragraph&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;button type="button" onclick="myFunction()"&gt;Click Here&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</pre>

<b>Example in &lt;body&gt; tag:</b>
<pre>
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;h2&gt;Example of JavaScript in &lt;body&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;

        &lt;p id="demo"&gt;A simple paragraph&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;button type="button" onclick="myFunction()"&gt;Click Here&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;script&gt;
            function myFunction() {
                document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Text has been changed.";
            }
        &lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</pre>

<h3>External JavaScript</h3>
Scripts can also reside in external files, this is useful when the script needs to be used across different web pages. JavaScript files have .js extension. 

An external script can be included in the HTML using the src attribute inside script tag. 

<b>Example:</b>
<pre>
&lt;script src="externalScript.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>

<h3>Advantages of External JavaScript</h3>
Using external JavaScript files provide several advantages: 

<ul>
    <li>Maintains separation of HTML and JavaScript code.</li>
    <li>Improves readability and maintenance.</li>
    <li>Allows caching of JavaScript files for faster page loads.</li>
</ul>

If you want to include multiple script files, use separate script tags for each:

<b>Example:</b>
<pre>
&lt;script src="externalScript1.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="externalScript2.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>

<h3>Referencing External Scripts</h3>
External scripts can be referenced in three ways:

<ol>
    <li>With a full URL</li>
    <li>With a relative file path</li>
    <li>Simply by filename if the file is in the same directory</li>
</ol>

<b>Examples:</b>
<pre>
&lt;script src="https://www.example.com/js/externalScript.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="/js/externalScript.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="externalScript.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>